                                                                                                               Nayachar deal Thursday
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Calcutta, Oct. 23: The Bengal government will sign a memorandum of understanding with the Centre on October 29 for the development of a chemical hub across Nayachar and Haldia.        
	The pact will outline the role and responsibilities of the state and the Centre on developing the hub.        
	Nandini Chakravorty, the executive director of the West Bengal Industrial Development Corporation (WBIDC), said: We will sign the agreement next week.         
	The Centre will invest Rs 2,508 crore in developing infrastructure for the hub. This allocation will be part of a five-year plan.        
	On the states part, private developer New Kolkata International Development (NKID), the joint venture by the Salim Group of Indonesia and NRI Prasoon Mukherjee, will build infrastructure on Nayachar island and Haldia.        
	Bengal is likely to be the second state to sign a memorandum of understanding with the Centre for a petrochemical hub. Andhra Pradesh signed one a few weeks ago. The Centre has also approved a petroleum, chemical and petrochemicals investment region in Dahej, Gujarat.        
	A management board will be set up to oversee work on the Nayachar hub. Union chemicals and petrochemicals secretary Bijoy Chatterjee went to Nayachar today on a recce.        
	Green clearance        
	Bengal officials expressed hope of being able to clear the green hurdle before the project.        
	The terms of reference for its environment impact assessment are ready. A private firm has been hired to do a detailed study that will form the basis of the assessment.         
	A state official said: The Union environment ministry may want us to do various studies and, based on their findings, ensure the necessary safeguards. As long as those measures are taken, the project is on.                                                                                                                                                                             
